# Variables & Environment
# Demonstrates file-level variables, nested resolution, and environment variable references.

### ── File-level variables ────────────────────────────────────
@host = httpbin.org
@baseUrl = https://{{host}}
@contentType = application/json

### GET using variables
GET {{baseUrl}}/get
Accept: {{contentType}}

### POST using variables in URL, headers, and body
POST {{baseUrl}}/post
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "server": "{{host}}",
  "message": "sent from Zed REST Client"
}

### ── Nested variable resolution ──────────────────────────────
@protocol = https
@domain = api.example.com
@apiBase = {{protocol}}://{{domain}}
@version = v2
@endpoint = {{apiBase}}/{{version}}

### Deeply nested variable
# Resolves to: https://api.example.com/v2/users
GET {{endpoint}}/users
Accept: application/json

### ── Variables in different positions ────────────────────────
@token = my-secret-bearer-token
@userId = 42

### Variable in URL path
GET {{baseUrl}}/anything/users/{{userId}}

### Variable in header value
GET {{baseUrl}}/headers
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

### Variable in request body
POST {{baseUrl}}/post
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "user_id": "{{userId}}",
  "token": "{{token}}"
}

### ── Environment variables ───────────────────────────────────
# Variables from http-client.env.json (public) and
# http-client.private.env.json (private) are also available.
# Follows JetBrains HTTP Client convention.
#
# Example: if your http-client.env.json defines:
#   { "development": { "base_url": "https://httpbin.org" } }
# and http-client.private.env.json defines:
#   { "development": { "api_key": "dev-key-123" } }
#
# Then {{base_url}} and {{api_key}} resolve when development is active.

### Using environment variable (requires http-client.env.json)
# GET {{api_url}}/data
# Authorization: Bearer {{api_key}}
